after the free international order
Cambridge – Many analysts believe that the free international order ended with China's rise and U.S. President Donald Trump's election.
If Joe Biden were to defeat Trump in the November election, should he endeavor to revive it?
Perhaps not, but he must find some alternative option.
Critics are right to point out that the American order after 1945 was neither truly global nor always very free.
It excludes more than half the world (including the Soviet bloc and China) and includes many authoritarian states.
American hegemony is often overstated.
Nevertheless, the strongest countries must lead in creating global public goods, or they will not be provided—and Americans will suffer as a result.
The current pandemic is a good example.
A realistic goal for the Biden administration should be to establish rule-based international institutions that involve different members for different issues.
Would China and Russia be willing to participate?
In the 1990s and the 21st century, neither country was able to balance against American power, which persisted in pursuing freedom values while disregarding sovereignty.
The United States bombed Serbia and invaded Iraq without the approval of the UN Security Council.
It also supported a UN General Assembly resolution in 2005 endorsing the "responsibility to protect," aimed at safeguarding citizens subjected to brutal treatment by their own governments — a principle the United States invoked in 2011 to justify bombing Libya to protect Benghazi citizens.
Critics have described this record as an act of arrogance on the part of Americans post-Cold War—such as when Russia and China felt duped by NATO's intervention in Libya, leading to regime change—and its defenders frame it as a natural evolution of international humanitarian law.
Nonetheless, the growth in Chinese and Russian power more strictly limits freedom of intervention.
What remains?
Russia and China emphasize the sovereignty principles enshrined in the UN Charter, which stipulate that states can wage war only for self-defense or with the approval of the Security Council.
Since 1945, the occupation of neighboring countries' territories by force has been rare, and when it does occur, it comes at a high cost due to sanctions (as seen in 2014 when Russia annexed Crimea).
In addition, the Security Council frequently authorizes the deployment of peacekeeping forces in troubled states, while political cooperation has also successfully contained the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and ballistic missiles.
This dimension of rule-based order remains crucial.
Specifically regarding economic relations, the world needs to revise the rules.
Before the pandemic, China's hybrid state capitalism had supported an unfair mercantilist model that distorted the functions of the World Trade Organization.
The result will lead to decoupling of global supply chains, especially in situations where national security is threatened.
Despite China complaining about the United States blocking companies like Huawei from building 5G communication networks in the West, the U.S. stance aligns with sovereignty requirements.
After all, China halted the operations of Google, Facebook, and Twitter for security reasons.
Negotiating new trade rules will help prevent the decoupling from escalating.
Meanwhile, despite the current crisis, cooperation in key financial sectors remains very strong.
Conversely, mutual dependencies in the ecological domain create insurmountable barriers in the face of sovereignty, as threats transcend national borders.
Regardless of how economic globalization is setbacks, environmental globalization will continue, as it follows biological and physical laws, which contemporary geopolitical logic cannot affect.
The above issues threaten everyone, but no single country has the capability to solve them independently.
In issues like the 2019 pandemic and climate change, power also has so-called positive-sum dimensions.
In such circumstances, simply thinking about exercising power over others is insufficient.
We must also consider exercising power in tandem with other countries.
The Paris climate agreement and the World Health Organization benefit us and everyone else.
Since Nixon and Mao met in 1972, despite differences in the ideological domain, this did not impair Sino-US cooperation.
Biden’s challenge is whether the US and China can cooperate in producing global public goods while competing against each other in traditional great-power domains.
Cyberspace is a new and important issue—partly because it has a transnational dimension, yet is also controlled by sovereign governments.
The internet has been partially fragmented.
Freedom of speech and privacy rules for the internet can be established within democratic countries, but these rules will not be recognized by authoritarian states.
As suggested by the Global Commission on the Stability of Cyberspace, certain rules prohibiting tampering with the basic structure of the Internet would also align with the interests of authoritarians if they wish to achieve connectivity.
But when they exploit proxies to wage information warfare or interfere in elections (actions that infringe on sovereignty), norms must be reinforced through rules akin to those negotiated during the Cold War to limit escalations of maritime incidents (despite lingering ideological enmity).
The United States and like-minded countries must openly declare the norms they intend to uphold and establish the necessary deterrence.
Maintaining free values in cyberspace does not mean the United States unilaterally disarming itself.
Conversely, the United States should distinguish between permissible forms of soft power through open persuasion and harder forms of information warfare, and it must retaliate when adversaries launch secret information warfare against it.
Russia and China can broadcast programs publicly, but manipulating social media and other covert unification behaviors are not permissible.
And the United States will continue to criticize these countries' human rights records.
Public opinion polls show that Americans want to avoid military interventions but do not wish to withdraw from alliances or multilateral cooperation.
And the public still cherish values.
If Biden is elected, the problem he faces is not whether to restore the free international order.
The question lies in whether the United States can work with core allies to promote democracy and human rights while also collaborating with a broader range of countries to manage rule-based international institutions needed to address transnational threats such as climate change, pandemic outbreaks, cyber attacks, terrorism, and economic instability.
